<Base title="CIY · Xiaochuan Li">
  <article class="prose">
    <div class="text-xs uppercase tracking-wider text-[var(--color-text-dim)] font-medium mb-2">
      Paper · draft
    </div>
    <h1>CIY — causal inferential yield</h1>
    <p class="text-[var(--color-text-muted)] italic !text-lg !mb-8">
      A graded measure over SC-grounded items, designed to be falsifiable.
    </p>

    <p>
      <em>Detail page coming.</em> CIY is a graded measure defined over the items that
      <a href="/research/sc-certification">SC certification</a> has already cleared as grounded. It
      asks not just whether the model is reading the licensing structure, but how much of the
      structure's inferential weight it is actually using.
    </p>

    <p>
      The design constraint is falsifiability. If we cannot construct two models matched on accuracy
      and on grounding but with opposing CIY, CIY is not a real measurement — it has collapsed into
      accuracy repackaging. The instantiation protocol is designed precisely to expose that
      collapse, not paper over it.
    </p>

    <hr/>
    <p class="!text-sm !text-[var(--color-text-muted)]">An interactive falsifiability widget will live here.</p>
  </article>
</Base>
